  "text": "We experimentally manipulated induced plant defences using a treatment with two levels (the 'induction' treatment). Plants were either assigned to a control group with no induction ('control' plants), or to a treatment group where we used the exogenous application of JA to induce defences ('JA-induced' plants). We prepared a 0.5 mM JA solution by dissolving 100 mg JA (Sigma-Aldrich #77026-92-7) in 2 mL of 99.5% acetone and diluting with 950 mL of distilled water; we also prepared a control solution that lacked dissolved JA but was otherwise identical to the treatment solution [CITATION_1] . This method has been used previously to induce defences in A. syriaca (e.g. [CITATION_2] . We applied either the JA or control solution to each plant by spraying every fully expanded leaf once (ca. 1 mL leaf À1 ) during each of three applications spaced at 2-week intervals (13 and 27 June, 11 July); the first application occurred while plants were still undergoing vegetative growth and before any plants had flowered. At the time of initial treatment application, mean plant height was 65.4 AE 14.4 [SD] cm and mean leaf number was 11.49 AE 2.43. We used intervals of 2 weeks to apply treatments because JA-induced chemical changes are maintained in other systems for at least 14 days [CITATION_3] .",
